04313nam a22005655i 9780300164954DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20122012ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001649547 a10.12987/97803001649542doi  a(DE-B1597)485984  a(OCoLC)1024022714  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aBS1135b.L56 2014 7aREL0400302bisacsh04a221.122231 aLim, Timothy H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Formation of the Jewish Canon /cTimothy H. Lim; ed. by John Collins. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Anchor Yale Bible Reference Library00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tList of Abbreviations -- t1. Modern and Ancient Views of the Canon -- t2. The Emergence Of The Canon Reconsidered -- t3. The Earliest Canonical Lists and Notices -- t4. The Torah in the Persian and Early Hellenistic Periods -- t5. The Letter of Aristeas and its Early Interpreters -- t6. The Wisdom of Jesus ben Sira and 2 Maccabees -- t7. The Dead Sea Scrolls and Authoritative Scriptures -- t8. The Holy Books of the Essenes and Therapeutae -- t9. Canon in the Gospels and Pauline Letters -- t10. The Formation of the Jewish Canon -- tAppendix 1: Some Modern Canons -- tAppendix 2: Early Canonical Lists -- tAppendix 3: Bryennios’ and Epiphanius’ Lists -- tAppendix 4: Extra-Canonical Jewish Writings and the Pauline Letters -- tAppendix 5: Scriptural References in Sirach 44–50 -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex of Subjects -- tIndex of Modern Authors -- tIndex of Scripture and Other Ancient Sources0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe discovery of the Dead Sea Scrolls provides unprecedented insight into the nature of the Hebrew Bible or Old Testament before its fixation. Timothy Lim here presents a complete account of the formation of the canon in Ancient Judaism from the emergence of the Torah in the Persian period to the final acceptance of the list of twenty-two/twenty-four books in the Rabbinic period. Using the Hebrew Bible, the Scrolls, the Apocrypha, the Letter of Aristeas, the writings of Philo, Josephus, the New Testament, and Rabbinic literature as primary evidence he argues that throughout the post-exilic period up to around 100 CE there was not one official “canon” accepted by all Jews; rather, there existed a plurality of collections of scriptures that were authoritative for different communities. Examining the literary sources and historical circumstances that led to the emergence of authoritative scriptures in ancient Judaism, Lim proposes a theory of the majority canon that posits that the Pharisaic canon became the canon of Rabbinic Judaism in the centuries after the destruction of the Jerusalem Temple.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCanon (Literature)xHistory. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh1 aCollins, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030016434340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030016495440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300164954423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300164954/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY